 turkey and' b'european and turkish jews?' b'' b"shaw: basically, i'm an ottoman historian, but i'm also jewish." b"i've spent twenty-five years studying ottoman history, and as" b'time went along, whenever i found materials on the ottoman jews,' b'i collected them. but i never did anything with them until a' b'couple of years ago, when i suddenly realized that was the' b'500th anniversary of the jews being expelled from spain and' b'coming to turkey. then the sephardic temple down on wilshire' b'avenue invited me to give a series of three lectures on ottoman' b'jewry. these lectures were greatly appreciated, and i became' b'motivated to undertake further research to develop a book, the' b'jews of the ottoman empire and the turkish) republic. this book' b'is quite different from the works of most jewish historians, who' b'tend to look at the jews in any country more from the viewpoint' b'of the jews and the jewish community, and rely mainly on jewish' b'sources. i view my subject as an ottoman historian, and i' b'approach the jews of the ottoman empire largely from the point of' b'view of ottoman society, using largely ottoman sources. after i' b'finished this book and sent it to the press, i came across' b'additional documents relating to turkish jews during world war' b'ii. in the completed book, i had said that turkey had done a good' b'deal to rescue the jews during world war ii, but i did not' b'actually have many details. then i found a batch of documents in' b'the foreign ministry archive relating to actions taken by turkish' b'diplomats to help the jews before and during the holocaust. it' b'was too late to add this new information to the book in press, so' b'i decided to write a second book. i conducted further research,' b'mainly in the archives of the foreign ministry in ankara and the' b'turkish embassy and consulate in paris. the result was the second' b'book, turkey and the holocaust, which details how turkey helped' b'rescue jews from the nazis.' b'' b'- how exactly did they do this?' b'' b'the story takes place over a number of years. the book presents' b'the material in three parts, first of which deals with the period' b'before the holocaust. when the nazis came to power in germany in' b'1933, they immediately started dismissing jews and anti-nazi' b'germans from universities, hospitals, scientific institutes, and' b'the like. turkey at that moment was just beginning the process of' b'reforming its universities, and it saw in these jews, who were' b'being fired from their positions in germany, a good source of new' b'talent to help modernize the turkish universities. within three' b'months after the nazis started dismissing these jews, turkey' b'arranged to take many of them in. they were brought to turkey and' b'were given appointments as professors in the turkish' b'universities, as heads of scientific institutes, and as medical' b'personnel in hospitals. about to major jewish professors' b'came to turkey in the 1930s. ernst reuter, a german political' b'scientist, spent the war years teaching political science in' b'turkey. after world war ii, he was mayor of berlin during the' b'berlin airlift. fritz neimark, a major german jewish economist,' b'came to turkey and helped establish a modern school of economics' b'in istanbul. a man named reichenbach, who was rescued from the' b'nazis by turkey and spent the war years in turkey, eventually' b'came to ucla, where he became a professor of philosophy. other' b'german jewish emigres engaged in cultural activities in turkey.' b'one such was karl ebert, who had been a leading theatrical' b'producer in berlin until he was expelled by the nazis. he went to' b'turkey, where he organized the turkish national theater and the' b'turkish national opera company in ankara, with the help of paul' b'hindemuth. so the first section of the book covers this first' b'phase, when jews were being persecuted in germany and rescued by' b'turkey. oddly enough, the german emigres, when they were in' b'turkey, did not seem to think too badly of germany. they regarded' b'themselves more as germans than jews, and they did not join in' b'the anti-nazi activities of the local turkish jewish community. i' b'even found letters from the nazi representatives to turkey' b'praising these german jewish refugees for their work in promoting' b'the idea of german culture. even though these people had been' b'persecuted by the nazis and rescued by the turks, they shared the' b"nazis' feelings of aryan racial superiority over the turks. the" b'second part of the book deals with the holocaust, which began in' b'1940 when the nazis occupied france. in europe at that time, and' b'especially in france, there were about turkish jews. they' b'had migrated to europe for various reasons from about the turn of' b'the century onward. most of them had settled in europe during the' b'turkish war for independence after world war i, when greece was' b'threatening to overrun turkey. the greeks had persecuted the jews' b'throughout the nineteenth century, and the jews feared what might' b'happen to them if the greeks took over in turkey. many jews fled' b'to france during the 1920s and 1930s. many also abandoned their' b'turkish citizenship and became french citizens. suddenly the' b'nazis invaded france in and started introducing all sorts of' b'anti-jewish laws. the turkish jews soon found that it was not' b'worth very much to be a french jew, but that it was worth a lot' b'to be a turkish jew.' b'' b'- how so?' b'' b'turkey remained neutral through most of world war ii. it retained' b'its embassies and consulates in all the nazi-occupied countries' b'until it finally entered the war on the side of the allies at the' b'end of during the war, therefore, turkey was in a position' b'to defend its citizens against anti-jewish measures, and the' b'actions that turkish diplomats took form the second chapter of' b'the book. turkish diplomats who were stationed in france in' b'particular intervened to protect jews of turkish citizenship from' b'the nazis. for those turkish jews who had retained their turkish' b'citizenship, there was generally no problem. if they were' b'arrested and sent to a concentration camp, the turkish diplomats' b'would communicate with the commanders of the camp and other' b'officials and say in effect: "these people are turkish citizens.' b'you can\'t do this to them." and the turkish jews would be' b'released. if their businesses were confiscated, the turkish' b'diplomats would protest and the businesses would be restored.' b'' b'the nazis in general wanted to keep the friendship of turkey.' b'they hoped to be able to use turkey as a gateway for an invasion' b'of the middle east, and they also wanted to obtain chromium and' b'manganese from turkey. in order to keep turkish friendship, they' b'usually accepted these interventions on behalf of turkish jews.' b'the turkish diplomats sometimes went to the concentration camps' b'to secure the release of turkish jews. at times they even boarded' b'trains hauling turkish jews to auschwitz for extermination and' b'succeeded in getting them off the train. most of the foreign jews' b'were sent to a concentration camp at a place called drancy in' b"paris, and that's where most of the intercession by turkish" b'consuls took place.' b'' b'the greater problem came with the turkish jews who had abandoned' b'their turkish citizenship and had become french citizens. the' b"consuls couldn't declare that these people were turkish citizens" b'because they were not. my book includes photographs of jews' b'lining up in front of the turkish consulate, either to get' b'passports to return to turkey or to get a restoration of their' b'turkish citizenship. this was a bureaucratic matter, so' b'processing the application would take some time. in the meantime' b'it was a real emergency, because the nazis would arrest jews on' b'the streets for almost nothing. the nazis would even arrest them' b'if they had radios or telephones in their apartments, because' b'radios and telephones were forbidden to jews. to take care of' b'these former turkish jews, the turkish diplomats invented a' b'document called gayri muntazem vatandash, or "irregular fellow' b'citizen." the document said in effect "this person is a former' b'turkish citizen who has applied for the restoration of his' b'turkish citizenship. in the meantime we would appreciate it if' b'you would treat him as if he were a turkish citizen." the' b'diplomats wrote the document in turkish and put their seals on' b'it. since the nazis could not read turkish, on the whole they' b'accepted these papers as certificates of citizenship. by this' b'means, the turkish diplomats were able to rescue many jews who' b'had relinquished their turkish citizenship.' b'' b'actually the nazis were of two minds about the turkish defense of' b'jews. on the one hand the nazi foreign ministry, which wanted to' b'retain the friendship of turkey, was in favor of accepting these' b'interventions. on the other hand, himmler and eichmann wanted all' b'jews exterminated. at times himmler and eichmann were able to' b'prevail and some of the turkish jews were sent off to auschwitz' b'before the turkish consuls could do anything.' b'' b'- do you have statistics on how many turkish jews were rescued?' b'' b'there were about turkish jews in europe before world war' b'ii, about of whom were living in france. most of the' b'information in this section of the book relates to the situation' b'in france. i have published the letters that the turkish consuls' b'sent to the nazi officials and the letters that came back in' b'reply. generally the nazis said that if the turkish consul would' b'present documents certifying that arrested individuals are' b'turkish citizens, and promise to send them out of france, the' b'nazis would release them from the concentration camp. the turkish' b'consuls also organized special trains to take turkish jews from' b'nazi-occupied territory back to turkey. these trains ran' b'regularly in and the nazis gave the turkish jews visas' b'so they could pass out of nazi territory, but the trains were' b'often held up by the nazi-influenced governments of eastern' b'europe croatia, serbia, and bulgaria because these' b"governments really didn't want the jews to escape. as a result of" b"the turkish consuls' efforts, about to of the turkish" b'jews in france were saved. another were sent off to' b'auschwitz, where most of them died. the remaining either' b'escaped across the border into spain or fled to the area of' b'southern france occupied by the italians, who treated jews much' b'better than the nazis did. at the end of however, italy' b'fell out of the war, and that was the end for those jews as well.' b'incidentally, the turkish diplomats in nazi-occupied greece also' b'worked to rescue jews in that country.' b'' b'- the second part of your book then deals with turkish diplomats' b'acting to rescue jews of turkish citizenship or turkish origin' b'from nazi persecution.' b'' b'yes, and there is an aside i might add here: in their' b'interventions on behalf of turkish jews, the turks cited their' b'treaty with germany which stated that turkish citizens in german' b'territory would be treated the same as german citizens in turkey.' b'on that basis the turks maintained that the nazis could not' b'discriminate against turkish citizens who are jews. the nazis' b'claimed (and the vichy government agreed) that they were not' b'discriminating because they were treating all jews equally.' b'turkey protested, saying, "you are dividing our citizens' b'according to religion, but the turkish constitution requires that' b'all citizens be treated equally, regardless of religion.' b'therefore, you cannot single out turkish jews." american consuls' b'in paris, by contrast, accepted the nazi argument and told' b'american jews who were being persecuted by the nazis that they' b"couldn't do anything about it, because the american jews were" b'being treated the same as other jews. the third part of the book' b'takes place in turkey, which was the principal center during the' b'holocaust for activities aimed at the rescue of eastern european' b'jews. the kwish agency, an organization established by jews in' b'palestine to help resettle jews to palestine, set up an office in' b'istanbul in under the leadership of chaim barlas. other' b'jewish organizations in palestine, especially the kibbutzes, also' b'sent representatives to istanbul to set up headquarters. these' b'groups first tried to contact jews in eastern europe to find out' b'what was happening. today we know about the holocaust, but at' b"that time people didn't know what was going on. they didn't" b'imagine the nazis could do the things they were doing. and so the' b'first step was to get information, and the turkish government let' b'them use the turkish mails to send letters to their relatives and' b'friends in eastern europe. the jewish organizations found out' b'what was happening when they received replies. later on when the' b'nazis began to intercept such letters, the jews received' b'assistance also from the vatican nuncio, angelo roncali, who' b'served as the vatican representative in istanbul from to' b'1944 and later became pope john xxiii. as the vatican' b'representative during the war, he used the facilities of the' b'catholic church to supplement what the turkish government was' b'doing to assist jewish agencies in contacting jews in eastern' b'europe. with the cooperation of the turkish government, these' b'agencies then sent hard currency, food, clothing, and even' b'railroad and steamship tickets to jews in czechoslovakia,' b"bulgaria, romania, and hungary. they weren't able to help much in" b'poland because by then the nazis had wiped out almost all the' b'polish jews. whenever possible the rescue agencies arranged for' b'the jews to get out of eastern europe either by train through the' b'so called orient express route to istanbul, or by boat through' b'the black sea to istanbul.' b'' b'turkey was not eager for all these refugees to remain within its' b'borders during the war, because it was being blockaded and was' b'suffering terrible shortages of food and clothing. the' b'government, therefore, facilitated the movement of the' b'non-turkish jewish refugees from turkey to palestine, either by' b'the taurus express railroad through the mountains to syria and' b'palestine, or by small boats across the eastern mediterranean' b'from southern turkey to palestine. these efforts were bitterly' b'opposed not only by the nazis, but also by the british, who did' b'not want any more jewish immigration to palestine because they' b'feared it would hurt their relations with the arabs. the british' b'constantly pressured the turkish government to stop this traffic' b'and send those jews back. in a few cases the turkish government,' b'yielding to british pressure, did send the boats back. for' b'example, in one incident, the steamship struma, with some b'jewish refugees from romania, was sent back by the turkish' b'government as a result of the intervention of the british' b'ambassador. when that ship was sunk by a soviet submarine, all' b'were lost except one person. nevertheless, all told, the turkish' b'government allowed no fewer than eastern european jews to' b'pass through turkish territory and move on to palestine during' b'the second world war. the turkish authorities also provided these' b'refugees with facilities and money, and gave them permission to' b'send money and food out of the country.' b'' b'- many of these jews who passed through turkey may still be' b'living in israel.' b'' b"yes, and their children. but let's return for a moment to the" b'first group, the turkish jews who came from europe. they did not' b'go on to palestine; they stayed in turkey. it was the' b'non-turkish, eastern european jews who passed through turkey en' b'route to palestine. their story is very interesting.' b'' b'- and you have rescued it from obscurity.' b'' b'many studies have been made of the holocaust, but most of them do' b'not focus on the eastern european or middle eastern jews. most of' b'the scholarship has centered on the western european jews, of' b'whom million were massacred by the nazis. my study deals with a' b'much smaller number of people. i have tried to round out the' b'picture, and i hope my book will persuade other scholars to' b'undertake further investigations in the history of eastern jews.' b'' b'when it comes to numbers, the german jews were also relatively' b'small in number. most of the millions slain were polish jews. the' b'rescue of eastern european jews may not seem so' b'significant compared with the total of million who were' b'murdered, but it meant a lot to those who were saved.' b'' b'about three-fourths of the book consists of documents b'translations of many documents. they are included because the' b'story is not well known. not only are people in the west unaware' b'of the courageous actions of the turkish diplomats; even the' b'people of turkey did not know the story. i felt that they would' b'not fully understand this remarkable achievement unless they' b'could see the documents.' b'' b'- what languages are used in the documents?' b'' b'most of them are in turkish or french; some are in hebrew. there' b'is a great deal of material in hebrew about the organization of' b'the boats going to palestine, the passengers, and so on, but i' b'did not go into those details extensively. i describe mostly what' b'turkey did, so most of my documents are in turkish or french. a' b'few documents are in english. the jewish groups in istanbul did' b'not necessarily cooperate with one another to rescue jews; in' b'fact, they often fought with one another. they took turns trying' b'to get the turkish government to deport rival groups. for' b'example, some of the kibbutz groups felt that the jewish agency' b'was run by western european jews who were interested only in' b'helping western european jews. finally, in president' b'roosevelt sent a personal representative, ira hirschman, who had' b"been an executive of bloomingdale's department store in new york" b'city, and hirschman managed to reconcile their differences. the' b'documents related to his mission are in english.' b'' b'i also obtained many documents from serge klarsfeld, a holocaust' b'historian in france, who mainly worked on the french jews. (his' b'father was killed by the nazis.) he gave me materials he had' b"gathered in the german archives on the turkish jews, so i didn't" b'personally consult the german archives. i believe that much more' b'can be learned from the german archives, and i hope someone' b'someday will make the effort.' b'' b"- this new book fits in well with your teaching, doesn't it?" b'' b"right. i'm giving a course on the history of the jews of the" b'ottoman empire. i first gave the course two years ago. in' b"addition to research, writing, and teaching, i've been actively" b'involved in the commemoration of the 500th anniversary of the' b'coming of the jews to the ottoman empire. among other things, i' b'helped organize a large international conference on the subject' b'which was held in istanbul in b'' b'- now that your books are finished and the conference has taken' b'place, what do you plan to do next?' b'' b"i'm working on two new books. one is a history of the turkish war" b'for independence, which took place after world war i, during the' b'years to the turks warded off the efforts of the' b'victorious european powers to occupy turkey and end its' b'independence. the second book is a study of sultan abdul hamid' b'ii, the last major sultan, who ruled from to he was an' b'important modernizer in his own way, although he also suppressed' b'all sorts of political movements.' b'' b'stanford j. shaw received a b.a. in history and an m.a. in' b'british history. he then shif